        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, I'm really glad you brought this up — two weeks of sharp knee pain is absolutely worth taking seriously, and it makes sense you're looking for answers.\n\nI have to be straight with you here: diagnosing what's causing that pain is genuinely outside my lane as a coach. Sharp pain that's lasted two weeks, especially on stairs, needs a proper assessment from a physiotherapist or sports medicine doctor — someone who can actually examine your knee, not just read a description of it. That's not me being overly cautious; it's just the right call for you.\n\nOn the ibuprofen question specifically — that's a medical decision, and I'd want you to get that guidance from a doctor or pharmacist rather than from me. What I *can* say from a coaching standpoint is that masking pain to keep training is generally a path that turns small problems into bigger ones.\n\n**Here's what I'd suggest right now:**\n\nPause the training plan until you've had that professional assessment. I know that's not what you want to hear with your half marathon on the horizon — but here's the thing: you have **16 weeks until July 11th**. That is a genuinely workable timeline. A week or two getting proper answers now is a much smaller cost than six weeks sidelined later.\n\nOnce you have clearance and any guidance from your physio, I'll be right here to rebuild the plan around whatever they recommend. We can absolutely still work toward 1:45 — your fitness base is solid and your recent training shows real consistency.\n\n**One thing worth noting:** you mentioned the pain started after your long run, and you do have a history of IT band tightness on that side. That context will be useful information to share with whoever you see — though let them draw their own conclusions from the exam.\n\nCan I ask — do you have access to a physio or sports medicine doctor, or is finding one the first hurdle to clear?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01MEDV2MgrVfM9QMNavpoC4v"
    }
